<HEAD>Soviet Authorities Expel Two Estonian Nationalists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT date of annexation.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities Saturday expelled to
Sweden two Estonian activists who were trying to organize an
independant Estonian party, a human rights group and the Swedish
national news agency TT reported.
   The two men, Buddhists with shaven heads, arrived on an Soviet
Aeroflot flight and were greeted by a crowd of about 15 Estonian
exiles.
   The Stockholm-based Baltic Helsinki Group quoted Eke-Part Nomm
as saying he and Vello Vaartnou had been told by the Soviet
authorities to leave the country or face imprisonment.
   Mr. Nomm, 22, said they were pressured into leaving probably
because he had read an appeal to form an Estonian Independence
Party at a meeting in Tartu Feb. 2, the human rights group reported.
   Numm and Vaartnou, 36, belong to a group of 16 Estonians who
work for the formation of a National Independence Party, TT
reported.
   The expulsions came shortly before the 70th anniversary of
Estonia's pre-Soviet independence day on Feb. 24, which is expected
to lead to celebrations and demonstrations. Similar activities are
planned in Lithuania, whose independence day falls on Feb. 16.
   The Soviet Union annexed the three independent Baltic states
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania in 1940 in a secret pact with Nazi
Germany.
</TEXT>
