<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-88 1436EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSBrothers     02-14 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Brothers,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Records: Eldest Ray Brother Suffers From AIDS-Related
Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eldest of three hemophiliac brothers
banned from attending elementary schools in a Florida county
because they carry the AIDS virus has now developed AIDS-related
complex, court records show.
   Ricky Ray, 11, has begun to show some symptoms of the disease,
but he does not have a severe or life-threatening illness stemming
from acquired immune deficiency syndrome, his doctor said.
   ``Ricky's ARC is stable, and he is showing no signs of
progression,'' said Dr. Jerry Barbosa, a specialist in pediatric
hematology and oncology at All Children's Hospital in St.
Petersburg. ``He should be able to continue performing daily
activities.
   ``He never posed a threat (of spreading the AIDS virus) in the
past, and he doesn't pose a threat to anyone in the present,'' said
Barbosa.
   Ricky is taking the anti-AIDS drug AZT, and Barbosa said the boy
is ``full of energy. His lymph nodes are no longer swollen.''
   Ricky's two brothers, 10-year-old Robert and 8-year-old Randy,
remain in good health, Barbosa said.
   Gail Lloyd, a spokeswoman for the federal Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta, said a diagnosis of ARC does not automatically
mean a patient will develop AIDS, a fatal disease that destroys the
body's immune system and leaves victims susceptible to infections
and cancer.
   ARC is a condition caused by the AIDS virus and has a specific
set of symptoms, Barbosa said. Those symptoms are often less severe
than the symptoms of AIDS.
   The AIDS virus is spread most often through sexual contact,
needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products and from pregnant women to their offspring. Doctors
believe the Ray brothers were injected with tainted plasma-based
medication they received to clot their blood.
   School officials in Sarasota County, where the boys attend
school, said Friday they expected some mild reaction from parents
once the news of Ricky's condition spreads.
   ``Every time there is a story about the Rays or AIDS in general,
there is some response from parents,'' said Lee Coose, principal of
Gocio Elementary School, where the Ray boys attend. ``But that
reaction has always been minor.''
   The boys' medical records are on public file as part of a
lawsuit filed against the DeSoto County School Board by their
parents, Louise and Clifford Ray. Barbosa filed the results of the
Ray boys' Feb. 2 physical examinations in federal court Friday.
   The Ray brothers were banned from regular classes in DeSoto
County in August 1986 after they tested positive for AIDS
antibodies. A federal judged ordered their return to the classroom.
   On the fifth day they returned, a fire destroyed their home.
Authorities ruled the fire was deliberately set, but no arrests
were made.
   The Rays moved to Sarasota with the boys and their 6-year-old
sister Candy, who is not infected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
