<HEAD>Songwriter Frederick Loewe Remains in Fair Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederick Loewe, who co-wrote the
musicals ``Camelot'' and ``My Fair Lady,'' remained in fair
condition Sunday after suffering chest pains last week, a Desert
Hospital official said.
   Loewe's condition was released by a nursing supervisor who would
refused to be identified.
   Loewe, 86, was brought to Desert Hospital late Wednesday because
of the pains and breathing trouble, according to his guardian, John
F. Morris.
   During an 18-year partnership, Loewe and Alan Jay Lerner wrote
such hits as ``Brigadoon'' in 1947, ``My Fair Lady'' in 1956 and
``Camelot'' in 1960.
   The team reunited in 1973 for a Broadway production of ``Gigi,''
which they had done as a film in 1958.
   Loewe retired in 1974. Lerner died in 1986.
