<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-88 1514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HermanTribute 1stLd-Writethru a0804 02-14 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Herman Tribute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0804,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stoltzman Plays at Woody Herman Tribute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to include time element</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Classical clarinettist Richard Stoltzman played
``The Ebony Concerto'' with Woody Herman's Thundering Herd at
Carnegie Hall in a tribute concert to the band's late leader.
   Saturday night's concert sounded the way Igor Stravinsky
undoubtedly meant it to sound when he composed it for Herman and
his band in 1946.
   Herman always said that, in rehearsals with Stravinsky above
Manhattan's Paramount Theater, and in the premiere at Carnegie
Hall, he and the band didn't really do justice to ``The Ebony
Concerto.''
   Herman had planned this Carnegie Hall concert, with Stoltzman,
not himself, playing in ``The Ebony Concerto.''
   Woody Herman's Thundering Herd now is led by Frank Tiberi, who
joined the band in 1969, primarily playing tenor saxophone and
bassoon. Tiberi, 59, called it ``a life-sentence membership.''
   Tiberi said that while Herman was sick he had said that his band
should continue _ ``and I'm going to continue with Woody's pattern
and his sound.''
   The 15-piece band isn't afraid to step into the classics, like
Faure's ``Pavanne'' or a flagwaving big-band arrangement of Copland
``Fanfare for the Common Man,'' played as the finale.
   Tiberi, two other tenor players and a baritone saxophonist
blended well on ``Four Brothers.'' The microphones weren't kind to
the band's playing of ``It Don't Mean a Thing if it Ain't Got That
Swing'' and ``Woodchopper's Ball.''
   Stoltzman also played a a medley arranged by band alumnus John
Otto which began with a solo ``Amazing Grace.'' Stoltzman played
that with exquisite, round tone and tenderness.
   After ``America the Beautiful,'' Stoltzman ended the medley
playing loose, inventive improvisations while the band came alive
and stomp-marched through ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.''
   Stoltzman also soloed on a Bernstein medley called ``Songs from
the West Side.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880214-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-88 1516EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan     02-14 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Relaxes After Mexican Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan went horseback
riding Sunday at his mountaintop ranch, relaxing after a weekend
summit in Mexico with President Miguel de la Madrid.
   After breakfast with his wife Nancy, Reagan saddled up for a
ride along the trails of his 688-acre spread in the Santa Ynez
mountains. Skies were clear and temperatures were warm, in the 70s.
   The Reagans, who left Washington on Friday, will remain at the
ranch until Wednesday when they return to the White House on the
eve of the unveiling of the budget proposal being sent to Congress
for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   As Reagan relaxed, White House chief of staff Howard Baker flew
back to Washington, leaving deputy chief of staff Kenneth
Duberstein, national security adviser Colin Powell and
communications director Thomas Griscom as the senior officials with
Reagan.
   Powell and Griscom are to return to Washington on Tuesday, a day
ahead of the president. The staff members stay at a Santa Barbara
hotel, about 25 miles from Reagan's ranch.
   Reagan arrived here Saturday evening after spending about four
hours at a summit with de la Madrid at the Pacific coast resort of
Mazatlan.
   The annual meeting _ the sixth and final summit of the two
outgoing presidents _ was marked by de la Madrid's bluntly worded
defense of Mexico's campaign to curb the production and trafficking
of illegal drugs.
   De la Madrid said Mexico's efforts were not appreciated, and
that the United States must do more to curb the demand for drugs,
which is at the source of the problem.
   Reagan replied, ``The people in the United States are now
turning away from drugs,'' a step he said should ``curb the demand
that fuels the trafficking.''
   As Reagan flew to his ranch Saturday evening, senior
administration officials who accompanied him departed on their own,
flying back to Washington or other sites. Secretary of State George
P. Shultz, Attorney General Edwin Meese III, Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III and Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter had
joined Reagan at the meeting.
</TEXT>
