<1ST_LINE>r a AM-George'sBirthday     02-14 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-George's Birthday,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Town Planning Celebration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This little town of 260 people will have a
community lunch complete with birthday cake, children's games and a
lengthy bingo session on Monday, Washington's Birthday.
   ``It's a big deal,'' said Winnie Davey, of the George Exxon
service station. ``The whole community is involved.''
   George, near the Columbia River in central Washington, was
apparently named after the first president, although some have
disputed that.
   Some assert the town was actually named after a dog belonging to
one of the founders.
   ``You shouldn't believe everything you hear,'' said Ms. Davey,
which may be a sad commentary on the birthday of a man who could
not tell a lie.
   But there is no doubt the town has taken much of its identity
from George Washington. Many of the streets are named after types
of cherries, including Royal Anne, Montmorency and Bing, said Ms.
Davey.
   Businesses have names like the Martha Inn, the Colonial Market
and the Cherry Tree.
   A highlight of Monday's activities at the community center will
be a large birthday cake created by Glenda Jenkins.
   The cake is in the shape of a mountain with George Washington's
face on it, said Ms. Jenkins, president of the organizing group
known as the Georgettes.
   ``The theme is George Washington's head on Mount Rushmore,'' she
said.
   The 18-square foot cake will be enough to feed 1,000 people, Ms.
Jenkins said.
   George actually throws a bigger celebration _ including a parade
_ during the Fourth of July, because the weather is better, said
Carol Michael, another organizer.
   At the Martha Inn restaurant, they'll be serving a noon special
of ham and cherry pie for $4.25 on Monday, said manager Carl
Keppner.
   The Exxon station will also have a special on pre-packaged
cherry pies, selling them two for 89 cents, said Ms. Davey.
   But it will just be business as usual at George Washington
Machinery.
   ``It's not a real big deal that I know of,'' said JoAnn
Lewandowski, a co-owner. ``I'm just going to work.''
</TEXT>
